data.title: Hits the spot every time
data.text: Classic Cuban cuisine.  Sandwiches are always on point.   Food is always fresh. Attentive staff.  It's not on the beaten path but worth getting out of your comfort zone for.

data.title: Nice littel local restaruamt with their own twist in some dishes.
data.text:
What turned me on to this place was one day I heard my aunt raving of it and saying how great their weekend specials are. Very home cooked meals that are not normally found in these little location. 

They have Ox tail dish that is to dye for. They also have this beef or chicken steak cut dish that they roll up and stuff them in all sorts of different ways. It can be with (Moro or White) rice, sweet plantains or Fufu which is yellow plantatins grounded up with pork bits. The thing is that the whole wrapped steak is then breaded and fried. (yes not a diet dish). The combination works for some reason.

On the weekends dont be surprised to see a whole rosted pig laying on a tray in the center of the counter space area in which they start to get portions from tehre to service on dishes or take outs. 

Bottom line, place is great, have eaten tehre several times and never has failed me. This is not a fancy place, but its enough to say its close to home cooking from the old style of what I remember.

data.title: great cubaen food

data.title: The fried whole snapper was awesome
data.text: This restaurant has little ambiance but if you crave a whole fried snapper and cuban side dishes then this place rocks. Good service and a range of the usual Cuban staples.

data.title: Neighborhood type Cuban Restaurant
data.text:
This is not a fancy restaurant, this is no thrills no frou-frou place where you get a tru Cuban food. made and served by Cubans. 
Went for dinner while in Miami and checked the places around and Casa Marin was shown as one frequented by the locals. 
Arriving at the place, this is a edge of the building place, with an open counter where you can get some Cuban sandwiches. Rustic wood tables, sat down grab the Menu and started looking at the typical dishes - very likely Brazilian food - and asked the pair of waitresses about each of them. They were very nice and friendly and proposed some of their good sellers. As for drinks, got some Malta, Iron Beer and Yerba Mate to accompany Milanese Chicken, platanos puree and Rice and Beans.
I can say the portions were humongous and I had a blast with the food and could see most of the patrons getting the same treatment as us (foreigners). Of course I can speak spanish so the connection goes faster, but you can see this is a place where locals come to have a good meal and talk. 
Don't go if you expect to be server as it was on a fine french restaurant, with a lot of show but a food that lacks interest. This place is to the roots, with Latinos talking loud, but that will give a great service with a Smile and a great food experience

data.title: Nasty!
data.text: This place is dirty, and the service is horrible.  Wait staff spends a lot of time arguing about whose "turn" it is.  Food was beyond horrible.  This is a shame, as I understand it used to be really good.  Even the sandwiches were bad - and it's difficult to mess up a Cuban sandwich.  A total and complete waste of time and money.  Never again.

BUT this past sunday 10/27/13 we where a group of 10 ,i decided to take my mother and her friends my son that came from college , and what a dissapointment !!! the bacon was un cooked on the rolled up pork, the garbanzo fritos , pasty like it had been cooked for days!! all of the dishes cameout cold, it wasen't the waitress fault she keeped saying am sorry , the only thing that wasent cold . was the beer glasses , she stated they had no beer glasses for beer so she goy us wine glasses instead !!! some guy dressed in white came out of the kitchen , and said the bacon was not toasted because it was fresh???? what about the garbanzos fritos? the cold palomilla? and the dark color in the garbanzos soup?

data.title: Best "arroz con pollo"
data.text: It is a cuban custom to eat "arroz con pollo" on Sundays.  Well, we decided to try Casa Marin's and it didn't disappoint.  It iwas a delicious traditional dish, just like I remembered as a child.  It is "chorrera" style which means "wet", made with valencia rice.  If you are looking for traditional cuban cuisine, you should try this restaurant.

data.title: VERY good!!
data.text:
Got lost and was hungry , so I googled a few resturants and VOLaaa A CUBAN RESTURANT THAT I HAD VISITED MANY YEARS AGO!!

We had the best dish , a rolled up pork steak rolled up in plantain, and picadillo , then wraped up in bacon and deep fried!!   the portions are large, one order will be enough for two!!  and just order another side,    thank God the waitress sudjested it..... 

honestly it was not greasy at all , the black beans where like home made , fast service and great live piano music!!

taking the inlaws soon!!

data.title: Best Cuban food in Hialeah
data.text: This is one of my favorite restaurant to eat very good Cuban food for a very, very good price.   However, on weekends it could be loudly than expected since locals go and sign songs from the past, some of them are really good, but you cannot hear what the people in your table are saying.  Excellent service.   They need more space.

data.title: Real Cuban Cusine
data.text:
I have been here a few times. Typical "real cuban" restaurant...great food, okay service, loud TV, very clean place, very cold beer and, again, great food.  Try the Cerdo Siboney. 
Everything here is good.

data.title: Great breakfast!
data.text:
We went to Casa Marin for breakfast. It was very early in the morning, we were about the first people there. The menu for breakfast was very good, ranging from Cuban to American.
The quality was good, I had a FRITA CUBANA, ( a kind of Cuban hamburger that has Spanish sausage, chorizo, and beef) It was great and it was ready fast. My wife had a Cuban sandwich which was abundant in ham and cheese. She could not eat it all and took the other half home. The restaurant is in heart of the city and is always full.  Last night I drove near the restaurant and it was packed, there were cars everywhere, that is a good sign.
